      "writtenOn": "2017-11-09T16:45:26Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There is still an argument for implicit conversions. Imagine if two different classes have a member function with a parameter named \u0027Invert\u0027:\n\n class Class1 {\n     using Invert \u003d GrYesNo;\n     void clipPath(SkPath, Invert);\n };\n\n class Class2 {\n     using Invert \u003d GrYesNo;\n     void makeClipMask(SkPath, Invert);\n };\n\nClass1::Invert and Class2::Invert both mean the same thing, so it would be nice for a Class1 to be able to just pass its parameter directly along to Class2.\n\nThe operator+ trick is clever. And you have a good point about using a struct instead, in order to have an operator bool(). If they\u0027re all typedefs anyway we might as well make an elaborate struct with operator bool()...",
      "parentUuid": "e50a4040_05d1e8eb",
      "revId": "7b28d56accbe51d7c1ca4bf88c8ff3da048a9709",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
